There is another interesting way of thinking about this.
"The Invariant Set Postulate: A New Geometric Framework for the Foundations of Quantum Theory and the Role Played by Gravity"
https://arxiv.org/abs/0812.1148
Consider that to have a deterministic outcome of any interaction we would have to have an infinite precision of all parameters of the action, which is impossible. What we have is a range which gives us a phase space. Now as mentioned, all calculations in this phase space are Complex (note the captial "C"). This gives us a boundary which is non-linear, or fractal in nature. If we plot the Mandelbrot between two sets of numbers we might get a picture in which half the plot is black and half is pretty picture. If we plot weather an electron tunnels through a semiconductor given a range of say, charge on the gate vs resistance of the material, we will end up with much the same thing. There is never enough precision to reach a deterministic outcome of either case. The answer does exist but since it is non-linear it is also non-computable. The only thing we can compute is the probability.

snippet.textDisplay: Measuring the properties of one entangled electron doesn't "determine" the properties of the other electron. Rather, because those electrons previously interacted with each other, they emerged from that interaction with their properties altered in predictable ways. Then, because they interacted with nothing else before one of them hit your particle detector, you can correctly infer the properties of the other electron based on your measurements of the first electron. The properties of the two electrons were already determined with respect to each other at the moment of their interaction, before one of them hit your particle detector -- you just didn't know what those properties were yet.

snippet.textDisplay:
A very clear explanation of the Many Worlds interpretation of QM.

It is so clear that, when I try to apply Popper's criterion of falsifiability to it, I see it cannot be done!

Just to make this perfectly clear: Popper's criterion of falsifiability consists of three parts.

1. A theory must not be contradictory. If it is contradictory, it consists of at least two parts that contradict each other. If you can find two facts, one consistent with the first part, and a second with the second part, then either fact falsifies the other part. Therefore both parts are false, which makes the whole theory false.

2. A theory must not be a tautology. If it is tautological, no falsifier can be constructed, which makes falsification impossible. Therefore it is a non-falsifiable theory, and therefore unscientific.

3. It must be possible to imagine a possible fact that contradicts the theory. A fact that is excluded by the theory, but nevertheless can be imagined to occur. (Only it hasn't, despite extensive attempts to find it. Finding facts in an attempt to contradict it, but failing, are called _corroborations._)

The Many Worlds interpretation of QM is

1. Contradictory, because it supposes that there can be one cat that is both dead and alive.

2. Tautological, because it explains every outcome, whatever it is, and excludes nothing. Both the dead cat and the cat that lives are predicted.

3. You cannot imagine an outcome that does not occur. When the cat is dead, the theory has predicted it. When the cat lives, the theory has predicted it.

In other words, the Many World Interpretation is as unscientific as you can get!

The reason why this whole defense of The Many World Interpretation might be appealing to many, is because it assumes a philosophical position called naïve realism. That is the metaphysical choice that says, that you can construct a theory whose content tells us exactly what the world is. In other words, that truth is possible. Or, that you can make an induction from facts to abstractions, beginning by your own experience.

But even Immanuel Kant showed in his Critique of Pure Reason, that this is a mistake.

He said: 'although all knowledge begins with experience, it does not arise out of experience.

From which he concluded:

We cannot know the world as it is! We can only know the world as it appears to us!

We observe many properties, for example, even as perceptions, that do not exist. One is color. Colors do not really exist. What we observe as different colors are just two very slightly different frequencies of light! Light consists of just one kind of phenomenon: electromagnetic waves of many frequencies and wavelengths. Moreover, we do not observe electromagnetic waves as just one type of experience. We do not experience infrared electromagnetic waves as light, but as warmth, which we observe by our skin, not by our eyes.

All theories do not originate from our senses, but always begin as fantasies. This means that, by their very nature, theories are built out of thoughts that do not come from our senses. No, they are, in their essence random creations of our minds! The 'stuff' all scientific theories are built from, are fantasies!

Such fantasies are useful when they satisfy the above three criteria, and only when they satisfy the above three criteria!

To be useful, the content of a theory does not have to tell us what the world really is!

Truth is an unscientific concept! This is because the very idea of truth is in violation with Popper's criterion of falsifiability!

And that is a huge advance, because it means that we can go directly from our experience of the world to certainty! A theory does not need to be true for us to be certain about whether it gives us a grip on reality or not! The _only thing that is important is: can we make predictions with our theories? Can we predict future experiences following from present experiences? If we can, a theory is useful. But a theory is never true, because it does not arise out of our senses! A theory only begins with our senses!

I want to add something else. Sean Carroll tells us that this theory is not in violation with the conservation of energy principle.

He explains it away, (very quickly) by asserting that we must look at the total energy of the entire multiverse. But if you do that, there is no splitting into many universes. There is just one huge multiverse, wherein every split is already there. It assumes a world picture wherein the past, present and future are equally real, metaphysically speaking. This idea of a total energy of the multiverse goes right against the basic principle of splitting!

So either you have a total energy of the multiverse, which exists as a metaphysically real past, present and future, and therefore there is no splitting. Or you have only a metaphysical present with splitting, but no conservation of energy.

So that already is a mistake!

HIs assertion that the Schrödinger equation does not imply that everything will happen. This is also a mistake, because if you go backwards far enough into the past, the Schrödinger equation excludes less and less, until you are at the Big Bang.

In other words, if we go back in time, and then see the universe as a branching whole, we do not know what the Schrödinger equation excludes! By assuming the present universe we experience, the Schrödinger equation excludes as Sean Carroll says. But if you start at some point in the past, you do not know.

So that is mistake number two.

By the way, the Schrödinger equation is already not the whole story. It is the classical approximation of QM. To do it properly, you have to include the special theory of relativity, which Dirac did. So you must start with the Dirac equation. But if you then go backward in time, then even less is excluded!

PBS Space Time just covered this topic a couple weeks ago or so. Matt’s angle of attack is slightly different. Like much of quantum mechanics, having multiple perspectives is helpful for grappling with the many worlds interpretation.

Food for thought: Given that, every time we branch, our branch inherits only some fraction of the total energy in the universe. How many branches does it take for a particular path to have so little energy as to not have any stuff in it anymore? There’s an interesting parallel there to the heat death of the universe. Of course, if the universe is infinite, a fraction of infinity is still undefined. So maybe there’s actually nothing to see here.
